<br>
I disagree with that. Do copy other people's stuff. But do it as a means to an end. If you copy someone elses style (like the DBZ style seems ripped off a lot by some artists, for example) you won't have anything original of your own. However, taking someone elses style as a blueprint and then turning it into something else is perfectly viable. I've seen a few different artists around here that are obviously influenced by DBZ style but have still managed to come up with something different. I personally found a lot of issues with my art solved when I leeched off of Yukito Kishiro's style; my art is nowhere near as good as his, and doesn't resmble it very often, but there are a lot of elements from his style that I've stolen and used in my own. I also take influences from Jm Mahfood, Bill Watterson &amp; Steve Dillon, as well as a few things I consider mine, and this makes a style that noone else has (bad though it may be. XD). The easiest way to create a new style is to create a hybrid. All artists have influences. :)<br>
